commentary.p:
Let P=(a,b) and let P'=(\cos t, \sin t) be the intersection of the line through0,P with the unit circle S^1 (where O denotes the origin, as usual). Let A=(a,0) and let C=(\cos t,0). Consider the similar triangles \triangle PAO, P'CO (draw a picture!). Let r=\left\Vert P\right\Vert, and note that the length of the line segment \overline{OP} is r, and that the length of the line segment \overline{OP'} is 1. By similarity, we have equal ratios of corresponding sides of the two triangles. \frac{a}{r} \amp =\frac{\cos t}{1}
\frac{b}{r} \amp =\frac{\sin t}{1}
From this we get P=(a,b)=(r\cos t,r \sin t).

statement.p:
Show that the following hold for all \alpha,\beta \in \R, {\mathbf x},{\mathbf y}\in \R^2.
\alpha({\mathbf x}+{\mathbf y}) \amp = \alpha{\mathbf x} + \alpha{\mathbf y}
(\alpha \mathbf{x})\cdot (\beta \mathbf{y}) \amp = (\alpha \beta) (\mathbf{x}\cdot\mathbf{y})

commentary.p:
    Let P=rW(t) and Q=sW(u) be the polar forms
      for P,Q. Then we have

	\mathbf{x}\cdot \mathbf{y} \amp = (rW(t))\cdot (sW(u))

	\amp = rs(W(t)\cdot W(u) \amp \amp (\text{by }
	  )
	\amp = rs \cos(t-u)\amp \amp (\text{by }
	  )
	\amp = \left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert \left\Vert
	\mathbf{y}\right\Vert \cos \theta.

statement.p:
Let n be a positive integer. For k in the range 0\leq k\leq n-1, let P_k=\wrap\left(\frac{2\pi k}{n}\right), where \wrap denotes the wrapping function.
Show that the points P_0,P_1,\ldots,P_{n-1} are vertices of a regular n-gon inscribed in the unit circle.
Show that the following holds for 0\leq k,\ell\leq n-1. P_k\odot P_\ell = P_{k+_n \ell}

li.p:
Draw sketches that illustrate the following.


(vector + vector = vector)
	      \overrightarrow{PQ}+\overrightarrow{QR}=\overrightarrow{PR}  


(point + vector = point) P+\overrightarrow{PQ}=Q 


(point - point = vector) Q-P=\overrightarrow{PQ}

Let P=(a,b) be a point, let \mathbf{x} be a vector, and let O=(0,0) be the origin. Draw sketches that demonstrate the following "conversion" formulas that convert the point (a,b) to the vector (a,b), and vice-versa.
(convert P to \mathbf{x}) \mathbf{x}=\overrightarrow{OP}=P-O
(convert \mathbf{x} to P) P=O+\mathbf{x}
